The question that we are investigating and trying to answer is: Can we predict a countrys CO2 output per capita based on certain factors?

#First we need to define all the packages that we will be using in order to answer our question.
library(ggplot2)

Now we must load in all of our data for analysis. The factors we chose to check were the countries alternative energy as a percent of the total energy, gdp, gdp growth, gdp per capita, gdp per capita growth, population, population density, population growth, urban population growth, and urban population as a percentage of the population. All of our data was collected from the The World Band DataBank and all countries available were selected.

alt_energy_per_tot <- data.frame(read.csv("DataNew/alt_energy_percentage_of_total.csv"))

Notice that there are some strong correlations between a few of the variables. This may prove a problem and we should remove one of those points to avoid multicollinearity.

Since we are using data looking at the same countries over multiple time periods, we have panel data and need to create a model based on panel data. That is where PLM comes into play. PLM is a panel data estimator that applies a linear model on transformed data. We use it to create our two models.

model1 <- plm(co2~alt_energy_per_tot+gdp+gdp_per_capita+pop+pop_den+pop_growth, data = newtotal_train, index=c("country", "year"), model ="random", effect="time")
model2 <- plm(co2~alt_energy_per_tot+gdp+gdp_per_capita+pop, data = newtotal_train, index=c("country", "year"), model="random", effect="time")

We see that our residuals are still quite large, but our predictions have gotten better. Improvements would include more variables to be included. Most of our variables were similar markers revolving around population, gdp, and alternative energy. We might want to divisify this portfolio to other factors such as number of vehicles, number of power plants, percentage of farm land, and more. The issue with these variables is the amount of data available. Unfortunately, a lot of this data is incomplete. Hopefully in the fututre we will have access to more complete data.
